      "item": {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "id": "31d9257605850d44",
        "text": "I volunteered to teach math enrichment classes at the elementary school in my neighborhood, unaware at the time that the school was entrenched in social justice controversy: a school with 85% latino families & children in the middle of an immediate neighborhood of >90% white households. This stratification was embarrasing in the middle of progressive Boulder, Colorado. I found myself deeply involved in conversations among adults in my community aiming to change this demographic imbalance. At a public visioning meeting I hoped to build a bridge of understanding across the racial divide... unfortunately I began by saying it was hard to be a visible outsider in the school at which point I was interrupted with a public shaming. Even as it was happening, I could see the point: poor white man can't handle being in the minority. In the heat of the moment I felt misunderstood, not actually ashamed. I also felt surprised and confused that I wasn't feeling more threatened by the experience. In the years I've had to reflect on the experience, it was the first time I became aware of being a symbolic role in a public debate, not an individual. I was an icon of The Patriarchy, and so shamed for being too fragile to endure the discomfort of being an outsider."
